this conversation will stimulate ideas.

00:01:06.062 --> 00:01:07.144
I want to say a few words

00:01:07.146 --> 00:01:08.520
about why weíre focusing on mentoring.

00:01:08.521 --> 00:01:10.273
This is actually the first of three

00:01:10.571 --> 00:01:11.885
faculty development events

00:01:11.885 --> 00:01:13.343
weíre holding over the
next few weeks

00:01:13.343 --> 00:01:14.462
The other two are focusing

00:01:14.462 --> 00:01:17.151
on book publishing
and media training:

00:01:17.151 --> 00:01:18.660
learning how to talk to reporters

00:01:18.660 --> 00:01:19.786
and people in the media.

00:01:19.786 --> 00:01:21.237
Weíre starting out with mentoring

00:01:21.498 --> 00:01:24.372
because we are using that to focus

00:01:24.372 --> 00:01:26.743
on the renewed commitment
of the university

00:01:27.173 --> 00:01:29.071
to a tenure track system

00:01:29.100 --> 00:01:32.822
and thatís something thatís a C-change
from the old Harvard

00:01:32.829 --> 00:01:35.990
I was at a conference last week
down in Washington

00:01:36.066 --> 00:01:38.573
and I saw a faculty member

00:01:38.710 --> 00:01:39.974
who is now at the
University of Michigan,

00:01:39.974 --> 00:01:41.899
who used to be a faculty member

00:01:41.899 --> 00:01:43.012
at one of our professional schools,

00:01:43.205 --> 00:01:44.850
who we tried to keep but who left

00:01:45.576 --> 00:01:46.974
And I asked how things were going

00:01:47.097 --> 00:01:49.218
and whether we could possibly
lure him back

00:01:49.218 --> 00:01:52.541
and he said, ìWell, where
I am is much better.

00:01:52.686 --> 00:01:54.772
It was much better for junior faculty."

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:57.606
And I said, "Well no, Harvard has a
tenure track system now."

00:01:58.195 --> 00:01:59.655
And he said, "What happened
to the eight-year

00:01:59.789 --> 00:02:02.355
Post Docs they used to give people?"

00:02:03.113 --> 00:02:06.228
We actually see this as a commitment

00:02:06.395 --> 00:02:08.857
to the development of people that we hire,

00:02:08.857 --> 00:02:11.604
that we hope to be promoting up
through the ranks.

00:02:12.008 --> 00:02:13.397
And we need mentoring programs

00:02:13.400 --> 00:02:16.827
because if we actually commit to
this kind of system,

00:02:16.876 --> 00:02:20.619
we need to make sure that our tenure track
faculty can succeed

00:02:20.793 --> 00:02:22.198
as they move up the ladder.

00:02:22.952 --> 00:02:24.185
In my own career,

00:02:24.423 --> 00:02:26.747
mentoring has been keenly important.

00:02:26.747 --> 00:02:28.348
In fact as I walk into the faculty club,

00:02:29.856 --> 00:02:32.153
I am always reminded of
my first encouters here

00:02:32.160 --> 00:02:33.186
which were breakfast

00:02:33.300 --> 00:02:36.476
with my graduate school thesis adviser,
Fred Marstellar.

00:02:36.700 --> 00:02:40.036
And we would meet for breakfast
in the main dining room

00:02:40.158 --> 00:02:43.310
at the ungodly hour of seven oíclock,

00:02:43.368 --> 00:02:44.880
which to me was likeó

00:02:45.178 --> 00:02:46.467
I coudn't believe it

00:02:47.140 --> 00:02:50.283
But Fred would very kindly
take me aside

00:02:50.285 --> 00:02:51.824
and sort of talk to me about

00:02:51.824 --> 00:02:53.576
my own professional development.

00:02:53.821 --> 00:02:54.907
when i was hired

00:02:55.589 --> 00:02:57.092
I actually knew I didnít want
to be a professor

00:02:57.755 --> 00:03:00.817
because of the way I saw Junior Faculty

00:03:00.817 --> 00:03:02.959
and the Harvard Statistics department
being treated.

00:03:03.485 --> 00:03:06.227
In fact the department has
just tenured last year,

00:03:06.281 --> 00:03:09.459
its first person from within
in about 45 years,

00:03:10.067 --> 00:03:12.651
just to recognize the kind of C-change.

00:03:12.697 --> 00:03:13.819
But I saw Junior Faculty

00:03:14.356 --> 00:03:19.088
and they were treated like
rotating day laborers

00:03:19.307 --> 00:03:21.694
and it just didnít make a
very attractive career.

00:03:21.986 --> 00:03:23.607
The reason I ended up going
into academia

00:03:23.607 --> 00:03:26.403
was because of mentors for people
who took me aside

00:03:26.490 --> 00:03:28.852
and said, ìJudy, youíd be really
good at this.

00:03:28.852 --> 00:03:31.407
You donít really understand
as a graduate student

00:03:31.549 --> 00:03:33.425
what life as a faculty member is like

00:03:33.495 --> 00:03:35.055
and so why donít you applyî

00:03:35.076 --> 00:03:36.674
in fact for the only job I ever applied

00:03:36.674 --> 00:03:37.674
was an Assistant Professor

00:03:37.683 --> 00:03:38.963
at the Graduate School of Education,

00:03:39.121 --> 00:03:41.526
where my faculty position is now.

00:03:41.664 --> 00:03:43.296
And there too I was fortunate enough

00:03:43.393 --> 00:03:45.573
to have mentors who really helped me

00:03:45.856 --> 00:03:46.856
and helped me understand.

00:03:47.396 --> 00:03:48.038
