ourselves together as:

00:10:05.943 --> 00:10:08.459
what is this school going to be?

00:10:08.628 --> 00:10:09.925
So, let me first talk a little bit about

00:10:10.125 --> 00:10:11.850
my personal experience
with mentoring.

00:10:12.921 --> 00:10:17.183
So, I went to MIT,
got a PhD in Physics

00:10:18.090 --> 00:10:20.709
and was recruited by
Bell Laboratories

00:10:20.982 --> 00:10:22.573
and went to Bell Laboratories

00:10:24.448 --> 00:10:26.957
just immediately after
graduate school.

00:10:27.868 --> 00:10:30.484
And my first week at
Bell Laboratories,

00:10:30.812 --> 00:10:32.795
I had an anti-mentoring
experience.

00:10:34.774 --> 00:10:36.806
Someone from the department
came in and said,

00:10:36.982 --> 00:10:38.527
ìSo youíre here. What are
you going to do?î

00:10:39.494 --> 00:10:43.059
And so I said, ìHereís the kind of
stuff I was planning on doing.

00:10:43.249 --> 00:10:44.706
Iím going to set up these
experiments.î

00:10:44.914 --> 00:10:45.914
This is what I told people.

00:10:47.213 --> 00:10:49.036
And the reaction of this
person was,

00:10:49.206 --> 00:10:50.538
ìWell, youíre never going
to survive here.î

00:10:52.756 --> 00:10:55.903
So, that was my anti-mentoring
experience,

00:10:56.136 --> 00:10:59.455
which I did not consider
to be very positive.

00:11:01.068 --> 00:11:02.068
and when I became

00:11:06.255 --> 00:11:08.267
I got on the leadership council,

00:11:08.555 --> 00:11:10.635
which is very much like the
faculty council here.

00:11:10.867 --> 00:11:15.318
I actually went around to all
of the new members

00:11:15.470 --> 00:11:17.902
ot technical staff in the
research area

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:18.731
and asked them,

00:11:19.085 --> 00:11:20.038
"Would you like a mentor?"

00:11:20.923 --> 00:11:22.487
And 100% of them,

00:11:23.435 --> 00:11:24.803
whether they are male, female,

00:11:25.099 --> 00:11:27.284
under-represented,
didnít matter, said yes.

00:11:27.823 --> 00:11:30.671
And so I set up a mentoring
program at Bell Labs

00:11:32.799 --> 00:11:34.950
which actually worked quite well.

00:11:36.438 --> 00:11:40.565
Then as I got up higher in
management there,

00:11:42.025 --> 00:11:44.167
I was assigned a formal mentor

00:11:44.311 --> 00:11:46.409
who was the head of a business unit,

00:11:47.530 --> 00:11:49.951
which I found to be extremely useful

00:11:50.301 --> 00:11:51.394
when I was a department head,

00:11:51.672 --> 00:11:53.526
which is like the third
level of management

00:11:59.542 --> 00:12:01.382
Bell Labs did not do very well

00:12:02.311 --> 00:12:05.748
until we actually put in a mentoring
program for the young people

00:12:06.089 --> 00:12:08.000
but by the time you got
in to management,

00:12:08.392 --> 00:12:09.392
they did extremely well.

00:12:11.139 --> 00:12:13.057
So when I arrived at Harvard,

00:12:13.674 --> 00:12:17.155
I discovered that we did not have
a mentoring program.

00:12:17.395 --> 00:12:21.241
That is to say we had an informal
mentoring program,

00:12:21.530 --> 00:12:24.679
where the former dean had said,

00:12:25.063 --> 00:12:27.636
ìWhy donít you go mentor
this person too?î

00:12:28.285 --> 00:12:29.365
But the person didnít know

00:12:29.683 --> 00:12:32.117
they were being mentored
and it was quite...

00:12:33.401 --> 00:12:38.073
So, what I set up is mentoring
networks which isó

00:12:38.822 --> 00:12:40.374
we donít have departments
in the school

00:12:40.558 --> 00:12:43.184
so I had to assign an associate dean

00:12:43.349 --> 00:12:45.396
to each tenure track faculty member

00:12:45.549 --> 00:12:47.670
so nobody fell between the cracks,

00:12:48.935 --> 00:12:50.848
and then they are in charge of a

00:12:50.967 --> 00:12:54.494
mentoring developmental
committee

00:12:56.877 --> 00:12:59.300
So, we all sat together as
associate deans

00:13:00.703 --> 00:13:02.857
and suggested names of people

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:04.908
for each of the tenure track faculty

00:13:07.363 --> 00:13:13.149
and then the associate dean

00:13:13.319 --> 00:13:15.801
sits with the tenure track faculty
member and asks,

00:13:19.162 --> 00:13:20.570
ìWhich of these people
would you like?

00:13:21.900 --> 00:13:24.519
Are you thinking of someone else
as your formal mentors?î

00:13:25.704 --> 00:13:28.976
So, three or four people are
on this mentoring committee,

00:13:29.626 --> 00:13:33.622
and I have a meeting every quarter
with the associate deans,

00:13:33.795 --> 00:13:35.648
with the chairs of these mentoring

00:13:35.791 --> 00:13:37.319
committees to see how
people are doing.

00:13:38.874 --> 00:13:41.236
So Michele asked me today,

00:13:41.362 --> 00:13:42.362
ìHow is this going?î

00:13:43.195 --> 00:13:44.757
And actually itís going very well

00:13:44.891 --> 00:13:51.268
except some of the tenure track
faculty were on leave,

00:13:51.435 --> 00:13:52.487
either maternity leave

00:13:52.631 --> 00:13:54.213
or some other leave

00:13:55.588 --> 00:13:59.650
and they kind of fell between
the cracks.

00:14:00.019 --> 00:14:01.019
That is to say,

00:14:01.267 --> 00:14:02.214
all of the associate deans

00:14:02.703 --> 00:14:03.424
at the very beginning

00:14:04.082 --> 00:14:05.995
went out when I asked them to,

00:14:07.941 --> 00:14:10.780
to talk to their tenure
track faculty

00:14:11.060 --> 00:14:13.635
but the ones who werenít there
at the time,

00:14:13.650 --> 00:14:15.738
they kind of forgot about it.

00:14:15.742 --> 00:14:18.745
So, I reminded the associate
deans again.

00:14:19.243 --> 00:14:21.201
And now Iím having lunches

00:14:21.504 --> 00:14:22.728
with the tenure track faculty

00:14:23.070 --> 00:14:25.079
and asking them how itís going,

00:14:25.412 --> 00:14:26.983
and I think it's going
a whole lot better.

00:14:27.240 --> 00:14:31.808
So, I guess the story line about this

00:14:31.969 --> 00:14:33.122
is keep following up

00:14:33.130 --> 00:14:35.003
if youíre setting up a
mentoring program,

00:14:35.219 --> 00:14:38.034
keep following up with
both the mentors

00:14:38.195 --> 00:14:39.835
and the mentees to make sure
itís working.

00:14:40.478 --> 00:14:41.478
Thanks.

00:14:51.699 --> 00:14:53.137
Good morning to everyone.

00:14:53.344 --> 00:14:54.344
My name is Julio Frenk.

00:14:54.488 --> 00:14:57.198
I have been Dean of the

00:14:57.366 --> 00:14:58.024
Harvard School of
Public Health

00:14:58.947 --> 00:15:01.811
for twice the amount
as Cherry,

00:15:02.454 --> 00:15:05.039
for about a year.

00:15:06.108 --> 00:15:08.381
So you have the table here
of new deans,

00:15:08.564 --> 00:15:10.211
at least on this side of the table.

00:15:11.427 --> 00:15:12.954
But thank you very much
for inviting me

00:15:13.452 --> 00:15:14.677
because mentoring is really

00:15:14.830 --> 00:15:16.006
a topic that is very,

00:15:16.613 --> 00:15:17.613
very near and dear to
my heart,

00:15:17.775 --> 00:15:20.589
probably stemming
from the opposite:

00:15:20.910 --> 00:15:23.218
a very, very fundamental

00:15:23.385 --> 00:15:24.938
mentoring relationship
I developed,

00:15:25.483 --> 00:15:26.483
first as a graduate student

00:15:27.034 --> 00:15:28.793
and then as a junior
faculty member

00:15:30.213 --> 00:15:31.916
with Avedis Donabedian

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:33.138
who was actually a graduate

00:15:33.283 --> 00:15:34.456
of the Harvard School of
Public Health

00:15:35.532 --> 00:15:37.144
And I went to the

00:15:37.208 --> 00:15:37.772
University of Michigan

00:15:37.942 --> 00:15:38.709
to study with him

00:15:38.859 --> 00:15:39.819
and under him

00:15:40.455 --> 00:15:43.721
and then I joined the faculty
with him.

00:15:43.812 --> 00:15:46.469
And I think it was probably

00:15:46.606 --> 00:15:49.223
not just one of the most
informative

00:15:49.971 --> 00:15:50.350
but one of the most

00:15:50.492 --> 00:15:52.133
formative experiences
of my life.

00:15:52.741 --> 00:15:54.942
So, I think having benefited

00:15:55.104 --> 00:15:57.469
from what a good mentoring
relationship is,

00:15:57.982 --> 00:16:00.919
Iím a strong believer in that,

00:16:01.193 --> 00:16:06.018
because academia is

00:16:06.138 --> 00:16:07.452
a highly competitive
environment

00:16:08.048 --> 00:16:10.267
and it is not obvious,

00:16:10.405 --> 00:16:11.886
even after having been

00:16:12.006 --> 00:16:13.153
there in the student role,

00:16:13.315 --> 00:16:15.267
how to navigate those waters

00:16:15.627 --> 00:16:18.288
without the sort of very,

00:16:18.474 --> 00:16:19.980
very personal guidance.

00:16:21.194 --> 00:16:23.319
Fortunately, the Harvard School
of Public Health

00:16:23.448 --> 00:16:25.516
has had a long tradition of

00:16:25.669 --> 00:16:27.013
emphasizing mentoring,

00:16:28.905 --> 00:16:30.305
particularly my predecessor

00:16:30.459 --> 00:16:33.069
Bary Bloom already in the year 2000

00:16:33.135 --> 00:16:35.228
fromed a committee to assess

00:16:35.271 --> 00:16:37.125
junior faculty mentoring.

00:16:37.876 --> 00:16:39.375
And based on the
recommendations

00:16:39.529 --> 00:16:41.074
from that faculty committee,

00:16:41.727 --> 00:16:42.748
each department was then

00:16:42.889 --> 00:16:43.651
required to develop it's own

00:16:43.817 --> 00:16:44.827
strong mentoring policy,

00:16:46.096 --> 00:16:47.256
which included assigning

00:16:47.568 --> 00:16:48.816
each new faculty member

00:16:49.427 --> 00:16:50.824
a mentor at the time of

00:16:51.414 --> 00:16:52.658
the faculty memberís
appointment.

00:16:53.935 --> 00:16:56.557
So, the school in additionó

00:16:57.004 --> 00:17:00.020
although it looks like a
play on wordsó

00:17:01.228 --> 00:17:03.438
you have to monitor mentoring.

00:17:03.948 --> 00:17:06.993
Monitoring mentoring
is a key aspect.

00:17:07.323 --> 00:17:09.138
So, there is what is called

00:17:09.479 --> 00:17:11.407
a bi-annual mentoring survey

00:17:11.738 --> 00:17:14.570
and through that weíve learned

00:17:14.668 --> 00:17:15.356
that a lot of progress

00:17:15.400 --> 00:17:16.423
has been made but also,

00:17:17.174 --> 00:17:17.940
thereís a lot of

00:17:18.890 --> 00:17:20.128
much more needs to be done.

00:17:20.856 --> 00:17:22.899
So, since I began my tenureó

00:17:23.076 --> 00:17:24.013
because I had the privilege

00:17:24.193 --> 00:17:26.128
of spending the full term

00:17:26.281 --> 00:17:28.642
of 2008 already being appointed

00:17:28.700 --> 00:17:31.187
but not yet having taken officeó

00:17:32.017 --> 00:17:32.967
I spent those four months

00:17:33.119 --> 00:17:35.606
coming every month for a week,
to Harvard.

00:17:35.774 --> 00:17:37.426
And mentoring was one of the topics

00:17:37.723 --> 00:17:39.363
that emerged right at the top

00:17:39.657 --> 00:17:41.260
of my early conversations

00:17:41.513 --> 00:17:41.906
with department chairs

00:17:42.034 --> 00:17:43.211
and with faculty members.

00:17:43.534 --> 00:17:45.933
So, I made this one of
my priorities

00:17:46.674 --> 00:17:47.598
particularly because

00:17:47.914 --> 00:17:48.961
the way Iíve expressed

00:17:49.504 --> 00:17:50.504
not so much the vision

00:17:50.573 --> 00:17:51.260
but the ambition for

00:17:51.421 --> 00:17:51.971
the School of Public Health

00:17:52.598 --> 00:17:53.623
is to make it the first school

00:17:54.161 --> 00:17:56.010
of public health of the 21st century,

00:17:56.291 --> 00:17:58.058
the first both in time and in quality.

00:17:58.200 --> 00:17:59.811
and you can only build

00:17:59.964 --> 00:18:02.226
the school of the 21st century

00:18:02.386 --> 00:18:04.146
with the generation of the
21st century

00:18:04.644 --> 00:18:05.235
and that generation

00:18:05.346 --> 00:18:06.446
is the generation of

00:18:06.570 --> 00:18:07.620
the junior faculty members.

00:18:07.921 --> 00:18:11.010
So, the only way to be effective

00:18:12.062 --> 00:18:13.814
in realizing that ambition

00:18:14.026 --> 00:18:16.256
is to actually invest in
junior faculty.

00:18:17.053 --> 00:18:18.699
So among other things,

00:18:19.012 --> 00:18:21.178
weíve established for
the first time,

00:18:22.032 --> 00:18:23.265
an office of an associate dean

00:18:23.805 --> 00:18:26.587
for research that funds
SEAT grants,

00:18:27.630 --> 00:18:29.030
provide scientific
editorials report,

00:18:29.732 --> 00:18:31.068
external review of
grant proposals

00:18:31.307 --> 00:18:33.509
and a number of support mechanisms

00:18:33.944 --> 00:18:37.098
for a school that's heavily
dependent on research

00:18:37.461 --> 00:18:38.131
and where promotion is

00:18:38.383 --> 00:18:40.368
heavily dependent

00:18:40.505 --> 00:18:42.144
on research productivity.

00:18:45.154 --> 00:18:46.664
Probably my diagnosis

00:18:46.857 --> 00:18:48.421
is that a lot of progress has
been made

00:18:48.817 --> 00:18:49.946
but the remaining challenge

00:18:50.168 --> 00:18:52.517
is heterogeneity across
departments.

00:18:52.697 --> 00:18:54.769
So, the quality of your
mentoring relationship

00:18:54.908 --> 00:18:57.141
should not have such variation

00:18:57.347 --> 00:19:01.339
because then also in the networks
of the faculty,

00:19:01.937 --> 00:19:04.775
the realization of very
different experiences

00:19:05.333 --> 00:19:08.443
is a factor in demoralizing
some people

00:19:08.617 --> 00:19:11.921
that donít get the quality
that they see peers getting.

00:19:12.490 --> 00:19:14.089
So, trying to achieve

00:19:14.089 --> 00:19:15.782
some uniformed standards-

00:19:16.243 --> 00:19:19.218
high standards is one of
my priorities,

00:19:19.400 --> 00:19:23.807
so some school-wide mentoring
guidelines have been established.

00:19:24.394 --> 00:19:25.980
And under these new guidelines,

00:19:26.571 --> 00:19:29.241
each new junior faculty member

00:19:29.378 --> 00:19:31.946
meets with a chair of the department

00:19:32.119 --> 00:19:33.496
soon after arriving at the school.

00:19:34.109 --> 00:19:36.548
At that time, a primary mentor
is identified.

00:19:36.737 --> 00:19:38.883
Sometimes thereís also a
secondary mentor.

00:19:40.090 --> 00:19:41.661
The mentors meet with the mentees

00:19:42.413 --> 00:19:43.763
at the beginning of their
appointment

00:19:44.074 --> 00:19:45.636
and then at a minimum,

00:19:45.811 --> 00:19:46.089
they have to meet

00:19:46.201 --> 00:19:47.604
at the end of each academic year

00:19:48.450 --> 00:19:50.077
to review academic progress

00:19:50.211 --> 00:19:51.694
and plan for the next year.

00:19:52.244 --> 00:19:54.474
So, thereís a formal structure

00:19:54.883 --> 00:19:57.817
but I think itís also very important

00:19:58.299 --> 00:20:00.516
to stimulate informal

00:20:00.516 --> 00:20:02.122
mentoring relationships.

00:20:03.467 --> 00:20:04.102
So in a sense,

00:20:04.703 --> 00:20:09.234
itís a multi-tiered strategy
with primary,

00:20:09.513 --> 00:20:11.150
secondary and informal mentors

00:20:11.602 --> 00:20:12.218
and in addition,

00:20:12.420 --> 00:20:14.367
members of the leadership

00:20:14.490 --> 00:20:15.661
of the academic administration

00:20:15.661 --> 00:20:16.168
of the school,

00:20:16.358 --> 00:20:18.120
particularly the senior
associate dean

00:20:18.413 --> 00:20:19.633
for faculty affairs

00:20:19.933 --> 00:20:21.610
and the associate dean

00:20:21.745 --> 00:20:22.925
for research that I just mentioned,

00:20:23.731 --> 00:20:26.273
meet with the junior faculty

00:20:26.395 --> 00:20:29.945
at critical points in their careers.

00:20:30.234 --> 00:20:32.464
So, itís this three layers of the chair,

00:20:32.631 --> 00:20:34.612
the formal and informal mentors

00:20:35.064 --> 00:20:39.398
and then the school-wide
academic leadership.

00:20:40.004 --> 00:20:40.335
But let me end

00:20:40.468 --> 00:20:41.987
because they did ask us to
talk a little bit

00:20:41.987 --> 00:20:43.059
about personal experience.

00:20:43.419 --> 00:20:44.874
And I thought what I would doó

00:20:45.315 --> 00:20:46.740
and this would take literally a minute.

00:20:47.596 --> 00:20:52.274
When my beloved mentor
Avedis Donabedian passed away

00:20:52.399 --> 00:20:53.742
after a very, very productive

00:20:53.879 --> 00:20:55.192
and rich life, I wasó

00:20:55.710 --> 00:20:59.212
having been his student
and pupiló

00:20:59.404 --> 00:21:01.243
to speak at his memorial

00:21:01.525 --> 00:21:03.876
and I reflected on the relationship.

00:21:04.291 --> 00:21:06.388
So, let me quote two
paragraphs fromó

00:21:07.144 --> 00:21:10.296
just a very brief mention
to what I said there.

00:21:11.884 --> 00:21:12.884
And this is what I said:

00:21:13.315 --> 00:21:16.093
Ours, referring to Avedis
and me,

00:21:16.372 --> 00:21:19.821
was the pragmatic
mentoring relationship.

00:21:20.400 --> 00:21:21.807
In our age of mass
education,

00:21:22.069 --> 00:21:23.657
the mentor has become an

00:21:23.792 --> 00:21:26.557
endangered academic species.

00:21:27.627 --> 00:21:28.983
A mentor teaches you

00:21:29.143 --> 00:21:30.734
but is much more than a teacher.

00:21:31.092 --> 00:21:33.317
A mentor befriends you

00:21:33.808 --> 00:21:35.321
but is much more than a friend.

00:21:36.276 --> 00:21:37.460
A mentor guides you

00:21:37.850 --> 00:21:39.627
but is much more than a guide.

00:21:40.300 --> 00:21:41.387
What a true mentor does

00:21:41.637 --> 00:21:44.099
is one of the greatest gifts
of generosity.

00:21:45.150 --> 00:21:46.590
He, I was talking about Avedis

00:21:46.918 --> 00:21:47.126
but we would say

00:21:47.245 --> 00:21:49.549
heís or she sows in your mind

00:21:49.775 --> 00:21:50.461
and in your soul,

00:21:50.934 --> 00:21:52.777
the seeds that will
nourish intellect

00:21:53.150 --> 00:21:54.751
and spirit for the rest of your life.

00:21:55.412 --> 00:21:59.241
So to me, this is the nature
of the mentoring relationship.

00:21:59.793 --> 00:22:01.699
And letís not forget
where this word comes from.

00:22:01.972 --> 00:22:03.528
Itís actually an individual--

00:22:03.656 --> 00:22:05.546
a figure in Greek Mythology
(Mentor)

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:08.636
who is entrusted with the
care of Telemachus

00:22:09.399 --> 00:22:12.182
when his father has to go to
the Trojan wars.

00:22:12.399 --> 00:22:15.757
So, although in this marvelous
plasticity of the English language

00:22:16.269 --> 00:22:19.127
weíve turned it into a verb
and an adjective,

00:22:19.461 --> 00:22:24.677
let us not forget that the root
of the word refers to an individual,

00:22:25.077 --> 00:22:26.596
and itís this personal dimension,

00:22:26.932 --> 00:22:28.598
this very, very profound,

00:22:28.873 --> 00:22:30.245
deep relationship that I think

00:22:31.255 --> 00:22:33.449
holds both to the
enormous potential

00:22:33.469 --> 00:22:35.932
and also the great rewards
of mentoring.

00:22:36.244 --> 00:22:37.244
Thank you.

00:22:41.971 --> 00:22:42.897
Good morning.

00:22:43.065 --> 00:22:43.487
So like others,

00:22:43.639 --> 00:22:44.065
Iíve been asked to give

00:22:44.219 --> 00:22:45.624
both a personal perspective

00:22:45.774 --> 00:22:47.158
but also part of a perspective

00:22:47.292 --> 00:22:48.672
from Harvard Medical School.

00:22:49.154 --> 00:22:50.527
And so Iíll say personally

00:22:50.625 --> 00:22:51.739
in terms of mentoring,

00:22:52.037 --> 00:22:54.491
as you look through the literature

00:22:54.528 --> 00:22:55.630
and you hear people talk about it,

00:22:55.717 --> 00:22:57.699
they talk about issues

00:22:57.826 --> 00:22:59.278
such as matching on gender

00:22:59.580 --> 00:23:00.840
and matching on race ethnicity

00:23:00.960 --> 00:23:02.315
and how important
those things are.

00:23:02.528 --> 00:23:03.852
And what I would say is,

00:23:03.945 --> 00:23:05.218
is if I look at my career

00:23:05.222 --> 00:23:05.950
and my progression

00:23:06.509 --> 00:23:08.701
if I were to find the
perfect mentor

00:23:08.845 --> 00:23:10.682
that was matched on all of
my dimensions,

00:23:10.819 --> 00:23:13.060
the only person that could mentor me is me.

00:23:14.878 --> 00:23:18.013
And so for me,
I have had multiple mentors.

00:23:18.037 --> 00:23:19.644
The idea of a network of mentors

00:23:19.772 --> 00:23:21.069
is the only way I have survived,

00:23:21.231 --> 00:23:23.541
and they have crossed
race ethnicity,

00:23:23.790 --> 00:23:25.253
and gender, and discipline.

00:23:26.534 --> 00:23:27.901
They have been individualsó

00:23:28.101 --> 00:23:29.894
and as you talked about
the anti-mentoringó

00:23:30.118 --> 00:23:31.857
that have protected me

00:23:32.128 --> 00:23:34.428
from what Bill Silan calls,

00:23:34.703 --> 00:23:36.133
the dementors and
the tormentors

00:23:38.862 --> 00:23:43.211
and they continued
as I moved forward in my career,

00:23:44.127 --> 00:23:47.282
critical elements for
my success and my balance.

00:23:47.675 --> 00:23:49.522
And those are the individuals
who early on,

00:23:49.748 --> 00:23:51.229
when I was at
Harvard Medical School

00:23:51.557 --> 00:23:52.557
and Harvard School of
Public Health

00:23:52.695 --> 00:23:55.071
and my interests were
very different from others,

00:23:56.264 --> 00:23:58.051
told me to pursue
my interests

00:23:58.195 --> 00:24:00.795
and backed me in pursuing
my interests

00:24:00.941 --> 00:24:02.657
and creating my own space

00:24:02.941 --> 00:24:04.294
for what I thought was
important,

00:24:04.652 --> 00:24:05.615
and actually showed me

00:24:05.783 --> 00:24:08.101
that there was a value to
advancing academically.

00:24:08.405 --> 00:24:09.651
Before then I had not thought that

00:24:09.758 --> 00:24:10.575
there was any value to it

00:24:10.898 --> 00:24:11.536
and it was my mentors

00:24:11.651 --> 00:24:12.567
who told me that there was

00:24:12.778 --> 00:24:14.867
and were able to show
me the way.

00:24:15.022 --> 00:24:16.556
I want to give you an example

00:24:16.685 --> 00:24:17.354
of some of the things

00:24:17.396 --> 00:24:18.081
that weíve actually done

00:24:18.884 --> 00:24:19.906
at the medical school.

00:24:20.156 --> 00:24:21.056
And the first begins with

00:24:22.282 --> 00:24:24.130
everyone saying that mentoring

00:24:24.249 --> 00:24:25.130
is critically important

00:24:25.357 --> 00:24:27.763
but not really recognizing it

00:24:27.900 --> 00:24:28.491
and our faculty affiliate

00:24:28.920 --> 00:24:29.491
really wasnít recognized.

00:24:30.300 --> 00:24:31.897
So, in 1995 our office

00:24:32.058 --> 00:24:33.873
established a mentoring award

00:24:33.924 --> 00:24:37.948
for the school that has
grown over time.

00:24:38.762 --> 00:24:39.750
It is an award that was

00:24:40.018 --> 00:24:41.760
establish in 1995
but has grown

00:24:41.944 --> 00:24:42.944
and since then,

00:24:43.042 --> 00:24:46.142
over 3700 nominations 
have come in

00:24:46.503 --> 00:24:49.174
for close to 1200 individual
faculty members.

00:24:50.116 --> 00:24:51.597
Itís grown from an
initial award

00:24:52.518 --> 00:24:54.175
that was named the
Cliff Barger award

00:24:54.335 --> 00:24:56.593
to having three categories
of Cliff Barger award

00:24:56.778 --> 00:25:00.013
for those who have
been in service

00:25:00.140 --> 00:25:01.659
for a minimum number
of years,

00:25:02.389 --> 00:25:03.886
a final award for those

00:25:04.007 --> 00:25:04.595
who have been in service

00:25:04.724 --> 00:25:05.661
for more than 20 years,

00:25:05.875 --> 00:25:07.717
and what we call a young
mentor award

00:25:07.878 --> 00:25:08.876
for those who have been

00:25:09.062 --> 00:25:11.291
in service for less than 10 years.

00:25:12.529 --> 00:25:15.951
To date, there have been
122 awardees.

00:25:16.464 --> 00:25:18.129
What I find important
about this

00:25:18.536 --> 00:25:20.232
is when we did our new promotion criteria

00:25:20.384 --> 00:25:20.942
for the school,

00:25:21.127 --> 00:25:23.479
these awards were recognized
within the promotions.

00:25:24.198 --> 00:25:27.388
And so how do you start to
recognize mentoring,

00:25:27.908 --> 00:25:28.808
and recognizing the way

00:25:28.950 --> 00:25:31.038
that it starts to show up
on individuals CVs,

00:25:31.340 --> 00:25:33.883
itís taken into consideration
for promotion,

00:25:34.196 --> 00:25:36.741
recognized throughout
our environment.

00:25:37.137 --> 00:25:39.746
Other ways in which it
has been recognized

00:25:39.938 --> 00:25:43.433
include CHAD which is a consortium

00:25:43.583 --> 00:25:45.449
or committee across the
Faculty Development

00:25:45.697 --> 00:25:46.405
and Diversity offices

00:25:46.690 --> 00:25:49.236
at the various Harvard
affiliated institutions

00:25:49.240 --> 00:25:49.991
with the medical school.

00:25:50.593 --> 00:25:51.361
And they actually offer

00:25:51.490 --> 00:25:52.133
a mentoring course,

00:25:52.322 --> 00:25:54.721
led by Jean Emmons
who is here,

00:25:54.903 --> 00:25:57.317
who was a silent
mentoring awardee.

00:25:58.245 --> 00:25:59.689
There is also a task force

00:25:59.814 --> 00:26:01.372
on Faculty Development
and Diversity

00:26:01.380 --> 00:26:01.966
that will be coming out

00:26:02.053 --> 00:26:03.429
with a report in the
next few months

00:26:03.870 --> 00:26:05.560
and one of the three
main committees

00:26:05.709 --> 00:26:07.597
of this task force deals
with mentoring,

00:26:08.021 --> 00:26:10.461
again chaired by
Jean Emmons.

00:26:11.404 --> 00:26:13.603
When we look at
mentoringó

00:26:14.256 --> 00:26:16.536
because I want to mention
some of the other people that are hereó

00:26:16.782 --> 00:26:19.598
and oftentimes,
we get an image of a sage,

00:26:19.765 --> 00:26:22.764
white man with white hair
and blue eyes

00:26:23.044 --> 00:26:24.190
and all the other kind of things

00:26:24.335 --> 00:26:24.952
that go along with that.

00:26:25.737 --> 00:26:26.947
And important part of this

00:26:27.093 --> 00:26:28.508
is recognizing that mentoring

00:26:28.659 --> 00:26:30.086
occurs all across our faculty.

00:26:30.203 --> 00:26:32.226
And one of the people that
we have here

00:26:32.353 --> 00:26:33.595
that I really want to point out

00:26:33.738 --> 00:26:35.009
is Jessica Henderson Daniel,

00:26:35.433 --> 00:26:36.689
who is the first woman

00:26:37.030 --> 00:26:38.118
and the first person of color

00:26:38.242 --> 00:26:39.420
to win the mentoring award

00:26:39.705 --> 00:26:40.663
at Harvard Medical School

00:26:41.115 --> 00:26:42.487
and recognizing it across the board.

00:26:42.660 --> 00:26:43.817
And Jessica,
you should go like thisÖ

00:26:49.782 --> 00:26:51.831
So, there are many ways
I think in which

00:26:51.989 --> 00:26:53.656
we are trying to
advance mentoring.

00:26:53.789 --> 00:26:56.196
The last part is actually
taking from those individuals

00:26:56.337 --> 00:26:57.196
who have won the
mentoring award,

00:26:58.075 --> 00:26:59.731
and now there is a
council of mentors

00:27:00.301 --> 00:27:02.255
that is actually meeting
and looking at

00:27:02.392 --> 00:27:04.301
what is going on
with the mentoring in the school,

00:27:04.718 --> 00:27:06.615
ways in which we can
improve mentoring

00:27:07.054 --> 00:27:09.074
but itís taken from the best
across our campus

00:27:09.388 --> 00:27:10.116
and across disciplines.

00:27:10.518 --> 00:27:11.518
Thank you.

00:27:18.252 --> 00:27:21.129
Well, I was appointed

00:27:21.251 --> 00:27:23.487
a year ago to this new role

00:27:23.882 --> 00:27:26.801
as Faculty Advisor

00:27:26.940 --> 00:27:29.101
on Faculty Development
and Diversity,

00:27:29.364 --> 00:27:30.920
and one of the reasons

00:27:31.080 --> 00:27:31.840
I agreed to do this

00:27:31.979 --> 00:27:32.674
is because I thought

00:27:32.699 --> 00:27:34.747
there was a really nice
theme in place

00:27:34.899 --> 00:27:36.486
with many people committed

00:27:36.601 --> 00:27:40.141
to creating cultural
change in FAS

00:27:40.667 --> 00:27:41.936
and this is not a minor thing.

00:27:42.385 --> 00:27:44.545
FAS is a very large part
of the University.

00:27:44.885 --> 00:27:46.146
Itís 40% of the faculty

00:27:46.279 --> 00:27:47.274
forty-two departments

00:27:47.455 --> 00:27:48.626
and these departments

00:27:48.805 --> 00:27:50.327
are very different in their culture.

00:27:50.335 --> 00:27:51.973
Some of them have never promoted,

00:27:51.973 --> 00:27:54.329
some of them have been
promoting regularly

00:27:54.335 --> 00:27:55.564
over the last few years,

00:27:55.715 --> 00:27:57.152
so itís really a complex mosaic.

00:27:59.559 --> 00:28:02.405
First my experience
with my own mentoring:

00:28:02.653 --> 00:28:03.140
Iím Canadian,

00:28:03.449 --> 00:28:05.345
I went to Paris as a
graduate student

00:28:05.995 --> 00:28:07.086
at a very young age

00:28:07.363 --> 00:28:08.804
and there was no mentoring.

00:28:09.281 --> 00:28:14.258
It was a pure swim or sink system

00:28:14.518 --> 00:28:16.512
and that was very difficult,

00:28:16.797 --> 00:28:18.007
it taught me resilience.

00:28:18.635 --> 00:28:20.708
And in 1983 I went to

00:28:20.875 --> 00:28:22.452
Stanford as a Post Doc

00:28:22.765 --> 00:28:24.227
and I discovered a word

00:28:24.435 --> 00:28:26.177
that was totally unknown to me.

00:28:26.505 --> 00:28:27.300
I felt those students were

00:28:27.444 --> 00:28:29.139
unbelievably lucky,

00:28:29.428 --> 00:28:30.603
privileged and also

00:28:30.739 --> 00:28:32.274
they were getting extremely
good training.

00:28:32.967 --> 00:28:34.528
Then in í87 I was hired

00:28:34.695 --> 00:28:36.315
at Princeton in Sociology

00:28:36.469 --> 00:28:37.524
where I was for 15 years

00:28:37.675 --> 00:28:40.026
before coming here in 2003.

00:28:40.816 --> 00:28:42.044
And Princeton at the time

00:28:42.179 --> 00:28:43.452
still had a system where

00:28:43.452 --> 00:28:45.396
only one person in six
approximately,

00:28:45.400 --> 00:28:46.555
got tenure and that was

00:28:46.667 --> 00:28:48.562
also a little bit baptism by fire.

00:28:48.738 --> 00:28:50.654
I really felt that they were

00:28:50.796 --> 00:28:52.400
not taking very good care
of us and many,

00:28:52.564 --> 00:28:54.979
many of my friends left
when we got tenure.

00:28:55.117 --> 00:28:56.676
All my friends were
gone basically.

00:28:56.923 --> 00:28:59.675
And then I came here in 2003.

00:28:59.800 --> 00:29:02.229
My scholarship is on
Culture and Inequality.

00:29:02.789 --> 00:29:03.827
I am presently working on

00:29:03.840 --> 00:29:06.355
anti-racism in France and the US,

00:29:06.469 --> 00:29:08.610
I really have a long-term commitment

00:29:08.873 --> 00:29:10.077
to trying to understand

00:29:10.284 --> 00:29:12.614
how collective definitions

00:29:12.741 --> 00:29:13.712
of worth influence

00:29:13.720 --> 00:29:15.196
for production of inequality,

00:29:15.453 --> 00:29:16.819
so my involvement in this

00:29:16.947 --> 00:29:18.841
is very much driven by
my own scholarship.

00:29:19.169 --> 00:29:22.048
I also happen to have a significant other

00:29:22.184 --> 00:29:23.900
who also studies diversity.

00:29:24.284 --> 00:29:25.980
And actually in the Globe
this weekend,

00:29:26.257 --> 00:29:28.650
there was a big article
on his work

00:29:28.785 --> 00:29:33.576
which basically shows that he
studied 800 corporations

00:29:33.697 --> 00:29:34.971
looking at which one have been

00:29:35.083 --> 00:29:37.767
most successful at
favoring diversity.

00:29:38.235 --> 00:29:39.559
And he finds that what is

00:29:39.671 --> 00:29:41.735
most effective is structural change:

00:29:42.069 --> 00:29:45.573
that is appointing people
who actually have as a responsibility

00:29:45.725 --> 00:29:46.800
or appointing task force

00:29:46.934 --> 00:29:50.527
who are in charge of
overseeing diversification

00:29:50.825 --> 00:29:53.897
and also using carrots
and stick to really create change.

00:29:54.102 --> 00:29:59.504
And mentoring is a very
big part of the equation.

00:30:00.126 --> 00:30:02.203
So, with all this backgroundó

00:30:02.394 --> 00:30:07.082
my predecessor Liza Martin had 
resigned in 2005,

00:30:07.850 --> 00:30:10.826
after having created a
mentoring program

00:30:11.099 --> 00:30:12.651
where women were matchedó

00:30:12.898 --> 00:30:15.245
only junior tenure track facultyó

00:30:15.633 --> 00:30:18.356
were matched with mentors
in other departments,

00:30:18.506 --> 00:30:19.356
which was a very good idea,

00:30:19.782 --> 00:30:22.631
because you can actually
ask advice to people

00:30:22.963 --> 00:30:25.787
who will not be involved
in your promotion

00:30:27.148 --> 00:30:28.900
where you can look
more vulnerable

00:30:29.454 --> 00:30:30.891
than the people who will be one 
day be in charge

00:30:31.024 --> 00:30:31.941
with looking at your work.

00:30:32.490 --> 00:30:35.463
Departments were asking FAS

00:30:35.463 --> 00:30:38.359
to report on their
mentoring activities

00:30:38.522 --> 00:30:41.945
but there was just an enormous amount
of informal mentoring occurring.

00:30:42.144 --> 00:30:45.334
And the literature shows us
that informal mentoring

00:30:45.567 --> 00:30:46.939
mostly benefits people

00:30:47.073 --> 00:30:48.681
who are entitled and many,

00:30:48.815 --> 00:30:50.491
many people did not
benefit from it.

00:30:52.365 --> 00:30:54.781
So, the idea was really

00:30:54.909 --> 00:30:56.426
to create a new system

00:30:56.560 --> 00:30:57.713
that was launched this fall,

00:30:57.947 --> 00:30:59.714
where weíre asking
both departments

00:30:59.714 --> 00:31:03.152
and individuals to
create mentoring plans.

00:31:03.409 --> 00:31:04.929
And actually, we donít
use the word mentoring,

00:31:05.146 --> 00:31:06.602
we use the word
development network,

00:31:06.947 --> 00:31:09.024
drawing on the work of David Thomas

00:31:09.160 --> 00:31:10.446
who is an expert
on the question,

00:31:10.455 --> 00:31:11.930
who works in the
Business School

00:31:12.090 --> 00:31:12.924
and Monica Higgins

00:31:13.037 --> 00:31:15.349
who works in the
School of Education.

00:31:15.609 --> 00:31:16.687
And the idea is that

00:31:17.481 --> 00:31:18.614
tenure track faculty

00:31:19.318 --> 00:31:21.002
create a network of people

00:31:21.111 --> 00:31:23.186
with multiple nodes

00:31:23.302 --> 00:31:24.967
that will answer various needs

00:31:25.196 --> 00:31:26.586
and the needs that are evolving

00:31:26.832 --> 00:31:29.545
as they move through the
tenure track system.

00:31:29.992 --> 00:31:31.768
And the word mentoring itself

00:31:31.906 --> 00:31:33.010
is not that great a word

00:31:33.171 --> 00:31:33.643
because in fact,

00:31:33.777 --> 00:31:34.953
what most people are seeking

00:31:35.099 --> 00:31:36.204
is intellectual exchange

00:31:36.853 --> 00:31:38.159
that is the ability to get

00:31:38.287 --> 00:31:39.413
people to read their work.

00:31:39.848 --> 00:31:41.879
When we work in my department 
to launch

00:31:42.023 --> 00:31:43.421
our mentoring plan this fall,

00:31:43.974 --> 00:31:45.598
this is what they want.

00:31:45.598 --> 00:31:46.841
They know that the faculty

00:31:46.938 --> 00:31:48.996
are unbelievably busy

00:31:49.187 --> 00:31:52.171
but they want us to really understand

00:31:52.317 --> 00:31:53.438
that weíre supposed to set aside

00:31:53.714 --> 00:31:55.753
few days a year to read manuscript

00:31:55.864 --> 00:31:56.710
and give them feedbacks

00:31:57.011 --> 00:31:57.835
so that they will be able

00:31:57.948 --> 00:32:00.772
to improve their work

00:32:01.031 --> 00:32:03.336
on which they will be judged

00:32:03.472 --> 00:32:04.617
when they come up for tenure.

00:32:05.320 --> 00:32:08.601
So, departments had until March 1st

00:32:08.894 --> 00:32:10.438
to turn in their mentoring plans

00:32:10.911 --> 00:32:13.519
and many of them have.
I'm very pleased.

00:32:13.829 --> 00:32:15.013
The cultural change is veryó

00:32:15.693 --> 00:32:18.614
the purpose in fact is not
to create these mentoring plan.

00:32:18.853 --> 00:32:20.926
Itís really to create a cultural change.

00:32:21.325 --> 00:32:22.988
And creating a structure in itself

00:32:23.139 --> 00:32:26.120
is probably the easiest
part of the challenge.

00:32:26.413 --> 00:32:28.457
What will be much more
of a challenge

00:32:28.847 --> 00:32:30.409
will be to monitor in a year,

00:32:30.950 --> 00:32:32.476
what has been happening.

00:32:32.760 --> 00:32:35.057
And there, Iím certainly going to
email my co-panelists

00:32:35.305 --> 00:32:36.093
to learn more about

00:32:37.426 --> 00:32:39.460
the tools that they have
put in place.

00:32:39.766 --> 00:32:40.859
I think that at Harvard,

00:32:41.572 --> 00:32:42.322
where thereís such a

00:32:42.467 --> 00:32:43.322
strong culture of excellence,

00:32:44.041 --> 00:32:46.255
diversity is often viewed
as a pollutant

00:32:46.480 --> 00:32:48.483
or even claiming aid-help

00:32:48.936 --> 00:32:50.009
is viewed as a pollutant

00:32:50.130 --> 00:32:51.960
because we all are supposed
to be so talented

00:32:52.119 --> 00:32:54.503
that the cream will
rise naturally.

00:32:54.835 --> 00:32:56.101
Well in fact everyone who 
gets tenure

00:32:56.230 --> 00:32:57.061
gets a lot of help:

00:32:57.649 --> 00:32:59.189
they get their colleagues
to read their work,

00:32:59.484 --> 00:33:02.256
they present their work
at colloquiam, et cetera.

00:33:02.620 --> 00:33:03.402
So, the idea is that

00:33:03.534 --> 00:33:05.751
to acknowledge that
getting help

00:33:06.034 --> 00:33:07.844
is crucial to the raising
of the cream

00:33:08.059 --> 00:33:11.115
but we want more of an
even playing field

00:33:11.420 --> 00:33:12.594
where more people
get the help

00:33:12.743 --> 00:33:13.172
that they need

00:33:13.315 --> 00:33:15.002
to become all they can be.

00:33:15.649 --> 00:33:16.985
And Harvard is I think,

00:33:16.985 --> 00:33:17.720
a little bitó

00:33:18.175 --> 00:33:18.893
if we think of whatís

00:33:19.026 --> 00:33:20.971
happening at
Stanford or at Yale

00:33:21.000 --> 00:33:23.412
our peer institutions are
fully engaged in this.

00:33:23.634 --> 00:33:25.475
Stanford has its motto:

00:33:25.818 --> 00:33:27.091
Diversity and Excellence
Together.

00:33:27.689 --> 00:33:30.480
And we are very much
moving in the same direction

00:33:30.769 --> 00:33:33.732
though FAS made a
very important statement

00:33:33.907 --> 00:33:35.755
last week to this effect.

00:33:35.916 --> 00:33:37.828
So, I think that

00:33:38.173 --> 00:33:39.542
a lot of people are pushing

00:33:39.931 --> 00:33:40.996
in the same direction

00:33:41.128 --> 00:33:41.887
and Iím personally

00:33:42.048 --> 00:33:42.968
quite optimistic

00:33:43.519 --> 00:33:44.092
for the future.

00:33:44.734 --> 00:33:45.834
Thank you.

00:33:51.493 --> 00:33:55.493
Panelists,
we are in factó

00:33:55.708 --> 00:33:58.039
as an FYIó

00:33:58.206 --> 00:33:58.732
we are in fact

00:33:59.012 --> 00:34:03.418
videotaping this section
of this event.

00:34:03.658 --> 00:34:08.672
And so we hope
to be able to have your faces

00:34:08.789 --> 00:34:09.818
on our website soon,

00:34:10.620 --> 00:34:12.620
so that others
who are not able to attend

00:34:13.005 --> 00:34:15.784
can be guided by your wisdom.

00:34:15.897 --> 00:34:16.432
So, thank you.

00:34:16.883 --> 00:34:20.858
We are privileged on many
fronts here at Harvard

00:34:21.538 --> 00:34:26.397
but I think that our human capital
at Harvard is unsurpassed

00:34:26.562 --> 00:34:30.722
and we do indeed stand
on the shoulders of many giants here.

00:34:31.011 --> 00:34:39.654
And often, we donít recognize
how they profoundly change our lives

00:34:39.978 --> 00:34:43.624
and how they profoundly
change our academic community.

00:34:43.897 --> 00:34:46.762
So, today we wanted to be
able to acknowledge

00:34:46.991 --> 00:34:48.176
some of these individuals,

00:34:48.359 --> 00:34:49.858
and I hope that we can
do more of this,

00:34:50.004 --> 00:34:51.004
as Joan had mentioned,

00:34:51.346 --> 00:34:53.679
we can do more to recognize
the mentors

00:34:53.842 --> 00:34:55.350
and those who support us-

00:34:55.535 --> 00:34:57.836
those who help us through

00:34:58.055 --> 00:35:00.430
the difficult challenges ahead

00:35:00.623 --> 00:35:03.549
as we try to develop careers
here at Harvard.

00:35:03.775 --> 00:35:07.202
So, I would like to have
Professor Scott Edwardsó

00:35:07.378 --> 00:35:08.971
as I call your name,

00:35:09.150 --> 00:35:11.421
if you could please stand
in the front

00:35:11.867 --> 00:35:15.347
so that we may embarrass
you further.

00:35:15.809 --> 00:35:16.809
Professor Scott Edwards,

00:35:17.049 --> 00:35:18.812
Professor Jean Emmons,

00:35:21.747 --> 00:35:22.747
Professor David Golan,

00:35:24.978 --> 00:35:26.528
Professor Virginie Greene,

00:35:28.780 --> 00:35:30.738
Professor Ichiro Kawachi,

00:35:31.411 --> 00:35:33.036
Professor Michele Lamont,

00:35:34.611 --> 00:35:36.220
Professor Everett Mendelsohn,

00:35:37.463 --> 00:35:39.008
Professor Joan Reede

00:35:40.434 --> 00:35:42.624
and Professor
Marianne Wessling-Resnick.

00:35:50.520 --> 00:35:51.528
For many years

00:35:51.663 --> 00:35:54.224
these individuals have toiled

00:35:55.270 --> 00:35:57.708
at many levels to support
mentoring,

00:35:57.857 --> 00:35:59.685
not just in their schools

00:35:59.819 --> 00:36:00.996
but in the University.

