and the Bach Center

00:37:54.701 --> 00:37:56.525
for organizing this very,

00:37:56.530 --> 00:37:57.643
very important event.

00:37:58.300 --> 00:38:01.264
And let me thank
in absentia those deans

00:38:01.396 --> 00:38:04.364
who either have been here
or will be here later

00:38:04.642 --> 00:38:06.466
because a high-level

00:38:06.621 --> 00:38:08.847
commitment is necessary
to this activity.

00:38:09.353 --> 00:38:09.863
Those of you,

00:38:10.000 --> 00:38:13.615
whether you are tenure
track faculty

00:38:13.948 --> 00:38:18.729
or people who have leapt over

00:38:18.863 --> 00:38:20.601
that hurdle at some time
in the past,

00:38:21.388 --> 00:38:23.487
recognize the importance
of mentoring

00:38:23.532 --> 00:38:24.720
and at the same time,

00:38:24.914 --> 00:38:27.474
recognize that it is
often thankless

00:38:27.642 --> 00:38:31.483
and that the rewards have
to be internal

00:38:31.650 --> 00:38:33.328
because you know youíve
done the right thing.

00:38:34.124 --> 00:38:35.787
As a university,

00:38:37.223 --> 00:38:40.586
we often donít find adequate

00:38:40.761 --> 00:38:42.408
ways to thank people

00:38:42.539 --> 00:38:44.168
for their extraordinary efforts,

00:38:45.699 --> 00:38:47.026
for their citizenship,

00:38:47.026 --> 00:38:49.108
for their caring.

00:38:50.900 --> 00:38:54.877
At least at a time of
famine and dirt,

00:38:55.037 --> 00:38:56.517
at least we have
muffins for you

00:38:56.830 --> 00:38:58.731
and unhealthy things

00:38:58.870 --> 00:39:01.704
like bacon to express our thanks.

00:39:04.182 --> 00:39:05.629
But in all seriousness,

00:39:05.916 --> 00:39:08.287
this is such an important area

00:39:08.327 --> 00:39:09.407
for the University.

00:39:10.056 --> 00:39:13.458
And before I launch
into my remarks,

00:39:14.174 --> 00:39:17.461
I want to particularly recognize
some of you here

00:39:17.627 --> 00:39:19.578
who have won mentoring awards

00:39:19.605 --> 00:39:21.245
and Iíve seen some of
you already:

00:39:21.497 --> 00:39:25.098
Everett Mendelsohn
from Arts and Sciences,

00:39:25.655 --> 00:39:28.080
Jean Emmons from HMS,

00:39:28.574 --> 00:39:30.997
Ichiro Kawachi
from Public Health,

00:39:31.923 --> 00:39:34.338
Marianne Wessling-Resnick
from Public Health,

00:39:34.490 --> 00:39:36.745
Scott Edwards
who I saw from Arts and Sciences

00:39:37.405 --> 00:39:39.653
and Professor Virginie Greene
from FAS,

00:39:39.861 --> 00:39:41.492
who I also saw a few
minutes ago.

00:39:42.373 --> 00:39:45.694
You areóand I hope
Iím not missing other names

00:39:45.877 --> 00:39:47.934
but you are really exemplars.

00:39:49.162 --> 00:39:57.258
I also again, want to thank
members of the leadership team

00:39:57.491 --> 00:39:59.954
and tenured faculty
who are here to talk about this

00:40:00.559 --> 00:40:06.575
Although the president
of the university

00:40:06.765 --> 00:40:09.061
is the person
who actually confers tenure,

00:40:09.351 --> 00:40:13.050
I chair half of the tenure cases

00:40:13.778 --> 00:40:16.394
except for the medical school,

00:40:16.807 --> 00:40:19.441
where actually Iím the last
signature on all of them.

00:40:19.594 --> 00:40:24.190
I mean, the good news is

00:40:24.319 --> 00:40:26.270
that at this last step of the ad hoc

00:40:26.583 --> 00:40:27.968
the success rate is very, very high.

00:40:28.743 --> 00:40:29.646
But all too often,

00:40:30.175 --> 00:40:34.184
we see people for whom the case is

00:40:34.318 --> 00:40:35.735
closer than it should be,

00:40:35.869 --> 00:40:37.435
despite their brilliance

00:40:37.719 --> 00:40:41.790
and their effort and sometimes,

00:40:42.522 --> 00:40:46.740
people who really should have
made it donít make it.

00:40:47.505 --> 00:40:48.221
And in some sense

00:40:48.350 --> 00:40:51.566
there are many reasons for
this but often,

00:40:51.898 --> 00:40:54.561
I thought to myself
after a difficult case,

00:40:54.753 --> 00:40:57.017
that had there only been
the right kind of mentoring,

00:40:58.430 --> 00:41:01.212
this would have had a
different outcome.

00:41:02.139 --> 00:41:08.139
And often, people are left to
fend for themselves

00:41:08.283 --> 00:41:10.875
or they have sort of glancing,

00:41:11.161 --> 00:41:12.161
intermittent mentorship

00:41:14.096 --> 00:41:16.471
and also from the point of view
of the mentors.

00:41:16.735 --> 00:41:19.712
Itís important to engage in 
groups like this

00:41:19.852 --> 00:41:20.603
and stay up-to-date

00:41:20.689 --> 00:41:21.285
and understand

00:41:21.572 --> 00:41:23.196
what the different schools

00:41:23.355 --> 00:41:24.676
are looking for becauseó

00:41:24.849 --> 00:41:27.869
for example in many other schools,

00:41:28.157 --> 00:41:31.112
Arts and Sciences in particular,

00:41:31.649 --> 00:41:33.611
teaching which at one time

00:41:33.744 --> 00:41:36.877
was considered to be something

00:41:37.045 --> 00:41:39.969
that you had to do

00:41:40.371 --> 00:41:42.030
but it wasnít worth all
that much

00:41:42.193 --> 00:41:45.689
is now an important part
of tenure cases,

00:41:46.869 --> 00:41:48.942
we just saw a new criteria

00:41:49.164 --> 00:41:50.035
from the School of
Public Health

00:41:50.331 --> 00:41:52.588
that made teaching important.

00:41:52.741 --> 00:41:54.128
So, each school has a different

00:41:54.268 --> 00:41:55.491
culture and different weights.

00:41:56.314 --> 00:42:00.095
And while tenure track faculty

00:42:00.278 --> 00:42:04.524
shouldnít enslave their energies

00:42:04.792 --> 00:42:08.664
and their interests to some plan

00:42:08.824 --> 00:42:11.568
for what it takes to achieve tenure,

00:42:13.516 --> 00:42:17.485
obviously people have
to follow their loves

00:42:17.675 --> 00:42:19.534
and their intellectual leads.

00:42:19.960 --> 00:42:21.320
Still, it is so important

00:42:21.469 --> 00:42:26.190
that people understand
the system

00:42:26.858 --> 00:42:31.584
and have the kind of helpful

00:42:31.868 --> 00:42:33.738
engagement in every stage

00:42:34.592 --> 00:42:37.699
so that we can achieve
what we want

00:42:37.869 --> 00:42:39.103
which is the success of all

00:42:39.256 --> 00:42:40.983
of our tenure track faculty.

00:42:42.643 --> 00:42:44.573
So in that sense,

00:42:45.372 --> 00:42:48.781
Iím really happy to see
this room full,

00:42:50.230 --> 00:42:50.635
and the only thing

00:42:50.635 --> 00:42:53.802
I could wish for is to see many,

00:42:53.947 --> 00:42:56.993
many more rooms full.

00:42:58.355 --> 00:43:00.069
Because in the end,

00:43:02.369 --> 00:43:03.729
we have committed ourselves

00:43:03.882 --> 00:43:07.073
as a University increasingly

00:43:07.209 --> 00:43:09.825
to a tenure track system

00:43:09.996 --> 00:43:11.761
or in some of the
professional schools,

00:43:12.096 --> 00:43:14.007
something like that
without a name.

00:43:15.123 --> 00:43:16.104
And what that really means

00:43:16.248 --> 00:43:19.792
is that we want to be committed
to our tenure track faculty,

00:43:20.075 --> 00:43:23.080
we want to get them through
these set of processes.

00:43:24.125 --> 00:43:26.165
But this is not a matter of magic,

00:43:26.358 --> 00:43:29.845
this is a matter of effort
and engagement

00:43:30.191 --> 00:43:35.695
where mentoring is
particularly important.

00:43:35.827 --> 00:43:37.035
And I think many of us

00:43:37.874 --> 00:43:43.378
think back to the importance
of senior faculty

00:43:43.699 --> 00:43:45.961
and mentors in our own careers

00:43:46.906 --> 00:43:49.141
and itís something though

00:43:49.281 --> 00:43:51.980
that just has not been
adequately institutionalized.

00:43:52.203 --> 00:43:56.966
And so I commend everybody
for being here.

00:43:57.344 --> 00:44:02.642
I wish you all a productive
and useful day

00:44:03.183 --> 00:44:05.829
and I hopeó
especially those of you

00:44:06.122 --> 00:44:09.194
who are already tenuredó

00:44:09.888 --> 00:44:14.257
I was told itís no longer PC
to talk about senior and junior faculty.

00:44:15.890 --> 00:44:17.756
But those of you who
are senior faculty,

00:44:18.026 --> 00:44:21.788
I hope youíll be evangelists
for the importance of mentoring

00:44:21.920 --> 00:44:22.785
in your schools

00:44:23.091 --> 00:44:24.223
because frankly

00:44:24.367 --> 00:44:25.255
as I said at the outset,

00:44:25.832 --> 00:44:27.245
this is not enough recognized

00:44:27.357 --> 00:44:28.276
or enough rewarded

00:44:29.045 --> 00:44:30.836
but it is absolutely critical

00:44:30.980 --> 00:44:33.788
if we are going to
succeed as a University

00:44:34.129 --> 00:44:35.624
in one of our most important goals,

00:44:36.113 --> 00:44:40.642
which is to help our tenure track
faculty make it over this bar

00:44:40.802 --> 00:44:42.806
and permanently join
our community.

00:44:42.817 --> 00:44:43.817
So, thank you very, very much.

00:44:49.310 --> 00:44:50.391
Well, I was in a group

00:44:50.687 --> 00:44:54.491
that included senior faculty

00:44:54.624 --> 00:44:55.527
and tenure track faculty

00:44:55.551 --> 00:44:57.750
in the Social Sciences
and the Humanities

00:44:57.900 --> 00:44:59.306
but across different schools

00:44:59.456 --> 00:45:01.647
in the Kennedy School FAS

00:45:01.954 --> 00:45:04.502
and the Harvard School
of Public Health

00:45:04.768 --> 00:45:06.059
and the medical school,

00:45:06.214 --> 00:45:08.551
and we had a really interesting
conversation,

00:45:08.726 --> 00:45:09.726
a troubling one too.

00:45:10.039 --> 00:45:12.937
Because some of the tenure track
faculty who were thereó

00:45:13.128 --> 00:45:14.395
I would say three of themó

00:45:14.558 --> 00:45:16.120
described context

00:45:16.272 --> 00:45:18.528
where they were really caught
between two chairs,

00:45:19.282 --> 00:45:24.193
in the sense of having
an appointment in a school

00:45:24.342 --> 00:45:27.532
where the discipline is
not marginalized

00:45:27.660 --> 00:45:29.397
but not dominant discipline,

00:45:30.125 --> 00:45:31.140
what path to follow

00:45:31.412 --> 00:45:33.532
when basically your chair
is very busy

00:45:33.970 --> 00:45:38.514
and is not immediately
available to give you feedback

00:45:38.668 --> 00:45:41.612
about whether you should
publish in your own field

00:45:41.861 --> 00:45:44.069
or publish for your school.

00:45:44.578 --> 00:45:48.669
Another case where a department
hasnít promoted since 1950

00:45:49.201 --> 00:45:51.601
and the person basically,

00:45:51.721 --> 00:45:54.611
doesnít know if his FTE will be
in one department or another,

00:45:56.095 --> 00:46:02.352
another case where the
output of the scholar

00:46:02.489 --> 00:46:05.866
is a very unconventional one
by Harvardís criteria.

00:46:06.089 --> 00:46:07.803
So for me in my role,

00:46:08.004 --> 00:46:11.222
Iím thinking we really need
a kind ombudsperson

00:46:11.430 --> 00:46:13.532
to whom people could go

00:46:13.676 --> 00:46:15.220
and raise a red flag early on

00:46:15.387 --> 00:46:16.627
to try to understand better,

00:46:16.796 --> 00:46:20.377
the criteria by which they
are going to be evaluated.

00:46:21.325 --> 00:46:24.579
A second issue that was raised

00:46:24.755 --> 00:46:28.281
is that of variation in the faculty

00:46:28.426 --> 00:46:33.353
in how much weight they put on
various criteria of publication:

00:46:33.475 --> 00:46:36.030
what kind of publication
books versus articles,

00:46:36.368 --> 00:46:37.903
service and teaching.

00:46:38.622 --> 00:46:39.695
And Judy Singer who was there,

00:46:39.833 --> 00:46:43.138
mentioned an experiment
they did in the School of Ed,

00:46:43.510 --> 00:46:44.980
where they asked all the faculty

00:46:45.086 --> 00:46:49.798
to attribute 100 points to
the various dimensions

00:46:49.957 --> 00:46:51.213
they used while looking
at their file.

00:46:51.375 --> 00:46:54.850
And they found it was a
very teachable moment

00:46:55.247 --> 00:46:56.743
when the results
were distributed and

00:46:56.872 --> 00:46:59.295
the faculty came to
the realization

00:46:59.463 --> 00:47:00.504
of how much difference

00:47:00.656 --> 00:47:01.792
there was in how much weight

00:47:01.832 --> 00:47:03.163
they put on the various criteria,

00:47:03.624 --> 00:47:04.963
which really made me think

00:47:05.112 --> 00:47:05.977
about the importance

00:47:06.117 --> 00:47:07.457
of spending much more time

00:47:07.824 --> 00:47:09.969
among the senior faculty,

00:47:10.227 --> 00:47:13.501
thinking much more
explicitly than we do,

00:47:13.511 --> 00:47:17.249
about what do we do
when we are evaluating.

00:47:17.539 --> 00:47:18.540
We have now in Affairs,

00:47:18.663 --> 00:47:19.773
a situation where some departments

00:47:20.020 --> 00:47:20.881
have never promoted,

00:47:21.018 --> 00:47:22.540
others have promoted
regularly.

00:47:22.749 --> 00:47:24.807
And I think among the
more senior faculty

00:47:25.001 --> 00:47:26.266
who have been here
for 40 years

00:47:26.394 --> 00:47:28.620
and those who have come
over the last 10 years,

00:47:29.070 --> 00:47:30.477
there are different expectations

00:47:30.612 --> 00:47:32.331
about what a Harvard
faculty should be

00:47:32.686 --> 00:47:34.701
and this really needs to be
talked about

00:47:35.029 --> 00:47:36.053
much more explicitly.

00:47:36.383 --> 00:47:42.165
So, thatís a second central
theme in our conversation.

00:47:42.311 --> 00:47:44.607
A third one was
how to find good mentors.

00:47:48.137 --> 00:47:51.202
Members of our group
mentioned the importance of gossip

00:47:51.727 --> 00:47:53.457
and of hanging out in hallways,

00:47:54.190 --> 00:47:58.702
and really how much good ideas
come at the most unexpected time.

00:48:00.255 --> 00:48:03.992
... who was
trained in New Zealand

00:48:04.322 --> 00:48:08.036
was regretting the good habit
of drinking tea together

00:48:08.179 --> 00:48:09.880
three times a day for
15 minutes,

00:48:10.066 --> 00:48:10.641
so we concluded,

00:48:10.763 --> 00:48:14.219
I think we should just institute
that here in all schools.

00:48:15.007 --> 00:48:16.272
Thatís basically what came up.

00:48:16.747 --> 00:48:18.218
I donít know if any of our
group member

00:48:18.331 --> 00:48:20.475
would like to highlight
any other point

00:48:20.620 --> 00:48:23.668
that I did not mentionÖNo.

00:48:32.067 --> 00:48:35.391
So, we had a very active
discussion,

00:48:35.759 --> 00:48:41.231
raising first the fact that there
are very different rules

00:48:41.279 --> 00:48:44.700
and ways of looking at
"ladder faculty"

00:48:44.845 --> 00:48:47.397
so that we didnít necessarily share
a common language

00:48:47.541 --> 00:48:48.683
from the medical school,

00:48:48.695 --> 00:48:51.208
the hospitals, FAS,

00:48:51.344 --> 00:48:52.263
the School of Public Health

00:48:52.458 --> 00:48:56.200
and therefore as mentoring
goes forward

00:48:56.342 --> 00:48:57.518
at Harvard overall

00:48:57.844 --> 00:48:59.952
and to make sure that
the language is more global

00:49:00.266 --> 00:49:03.435
and more really
accepting of the entire group.

00:49:04.395 --> 00:49:07.121
And so just in terms of
the common language,

00:49:07.160 --> 00:49:11.119
the issues of promotion
versus career satisfaction

00:49:11.266 --> 00:49:14.203
and really accepting
some heterogeneity

00:49:14.574 --> 00:49:17.569
in the definition of
what we want for mentoring.

00:49:18.352 --> 00:49:21.870
It was clear that there should
be expectations Harvard wide,

00:49:22.028 --> 00:49:22.949
of a change of culture

00:49:23.092 --> 00:49:24.516
that mentoring was important

00:49:25.434 --> 00:49:27.454
across all career trajectories.

00:49:28.418 --> 00:49:30.957
A lot of interest in mentor

00:49:30.957 --> 00:49:32.501
and mentee training,

00:49:33.150 --> 00:49:35.592
so that again there was
more uniformity

00:49:35.762 --> 00:49:38.596
both in our senior faculty of
knowing how to really

00:49:38.740 --> 00:49:39.954
effectively mentor

00:49:40.175 --> 00:49:44.793
but for our junior faculty
to have more information

00:49:45.018 --> 00:49:47.904
on how to be  a great mentor
and what to expect.

00:49:48.405 --> 00:49:51.030
And this could be in the form of

00:49:51.366 --> 00:49:53.325
part of the boot camp 
thatís part ofó

00:49:53.561 --> 00:49:57.056
apparently when the new faculty
come to FAS

00:49:57.259 --> 00:50:00.416
and some other areas,
perhaps orientation at the hospitals

00:50:00.708 --> 00:50:04.456
so that thereís sort of a module
that explains some of the ways

00:50:04.589 --> 00:50:07.563
that one can think about
being a mentee.

00:50:08.830 --> 00:50:11.839
The other issue is to certainly
leverage the infrastructure

00:50:12.040 --> 00:50:15.393
of already the hospitals,
the departments, et cetera

00:50:15.643 --> 00:50:17.358
and just to make it part of the

00:50:17.522 --> 00:50:21.347
faculty discussions,
part of sort of every area,

00:50:21.626 --> 00:50:22.666
whether itís a faculty meeting,

00:50:22.837 --> 00:50:24.415
perhaps you can do
mentor training

00:50:24.575 --> 00:50:27.201
because the faculty are already
there at the faculty meeting

00:50:27.885 --> 00:50:30.605
and theyíre not likely to show
up at other places sometimes.

00:50:31.696 --> 00:50:34.562
And then we talked about
some of the various models

00:50:34.984 --> 00:50:39.281
which could be junior faculty
doing peer mentoring.

00:50:39.863 --> 00:50:42.491
There could be a senior person
there or not there,

00:50:42.644 --> 00:50:44.774
so it could serve a
networking focus

00:50:44.940 --> 00:50:47.804
and also to help the junior
faculty develop skills.

00:50:47.998 --> 00:50:50.750
There was a sense that many of the
junior faculty were told,

00:50:50.920 --> 00:50:54.511
ìWell, donít mentor anyone because
that will ruin your own career.î

00:50:54.754 --> 00:50:56.869
And so weíre giving sort of
an early message

00:50:57.238 --> 00:51:00.592
and thatís not really what we want
to develop in the long run.

00:51:01.108 --> 00:51:03.732
And then Jessica brought
up some issues

00:51:03.862 --> 00:51:05.087
around serial mentoring.

00:51:06.050 --> 00:51:08.160
You may think of it from the
adolescent point of view,

00:51:08.321 --> 00:51:09.038
which is where I think of it,

00:51:09.501 --> 00:51:11.607
which is serial monogamy.

00:51:12.790 --> 00:51:17.263
But certainly, to think
about the fact that

00:51:17.398 --> 00:51:20.567
one needs developmental networks
